<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Airlines to stop sales in naira
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL ADAMS and REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LAGOS, LUANDA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
International airlines in Nigeria are to stop ticket sales in local currency
from February 1 to prevent a backlog of naira earnings until the government
clarifies its new foreign exchange regulations.
The decision follows warnings by businessmen that exchange rate and interest
rate controls introduced in last week's budget are unworkable, and will
severely erode legitimate foreign trade.
Mr Ebenezer Babatope, transport minister, has threatened to penalise the
Board of Airline Representatives for action he called 'embarrassing but also
illegal and out of tune with the aspirations of this year's budget'.
If he overrules the ban on naira sales, airlines could restrict ticket sales
to outside Nigeria. The airlines told the government last July they were
worried about a remittance backlog worth the naira equivalent of Dollars 50m
(Pounds 33.3m) by the start of January.
The airlines believe the 1994 budget could worsen their position as it makes
no provision for invisible earnings. It allots 80 per cent of foreign
exchange to manufacturing and agriculture. Nigeria's deepening economic
crisis has led to fears of rapid naira depreciation. 'Our decision is just
to limit the damage,' an airline official said in Lagos yesterday.
'The airlines in Nigeria need an average of Dollars 30m a month to remit
their local currency ticket sales to Europe. According to the budget, we
won't get anything like that amount and we will be left with an even bigger
naira balance.'
The government fixes Nigeria-Europe fares at less than the sale price in
Europe. Airlines must also base the naira price on an official dollar rate
of N22. Last year the market rate was around N45.
Angola said yesterday it had abolished differential exchange rates for
foreign currency and introduced a single floating exchange regime, Reuter
writes from Luanda.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>NGZ  Nigeria, Africa.
</CN>
