<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / Reformer quits rather than cry surrender
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Apres moi le deluge was the message from Mr Boris Fyodorov, Russia's
35-year-old finance minister, whose resignation last night leaves a gaping
hole in the country's economic reform programme.
A pugnacious champion of market reform, he said he was quitting not just
because his conditions for staying had been rejected, but because the
government was planning to abandon his tough financial policy. 'There is a
fine line between a moderate policy and an inflationary policy,' he said,
expressing hopes that 'the few remaining professionals in the government'
would try to prevent the 'catastrophe' of hyperinflation.
Announcing his resignation, Mr Fyodorov predicted that attempts to fight
inflation by means other than tough monetary and fiscal policies would lead
to a surge in inflation in the second quarter, from its present level of
around 20 per cent a month.
'Nothing' would stop the fall in the rouble, which has lost a third of its
value against the dollar in the past three weeks, unless, he added
sarcastically, Mr Victor Gerashchenko, the central bank chairman whose
removal he had demanded, kept 'his promise of a return to a fixed exchange
rate'. Moves towards a domestically convertible currency have been one of
the main components of reform in the past two years.
Mr Fyodorov doubted Russia could count on significant help from
international organisations such as the International Monetary Fund to
support a changed course. Hours earlier, Mr Victor Chernomyrdin, who angrily
rejected Mr Fyodorov's attempts to dictate conditions for staying in his
government, sought to pre-empt such remarks by vowing he was not retreating
from market reforms but correcting them.
'The age of market romanticism is over,' Mr Chernomyrdin declared. He denied
he was planning to spend his way out of crisis, saying it is 'not true that
Chernomyrdin will give money here and there'. The government had to embrace
other tried and tested methods for fighting inflation, including promoting
competition, pursuing an industrial policy and, he hinted, wage limits to be
agreed between government, unions and workers.
'Fyodorov's departure shows the government is determined to change tack and
see if there are other ways to control inflation,' said one western
economist. 'I would expect what they are saying: more support for industry
and agriculture, and less reliance on markets to determine economic
restructuring. It is a change of direction rather than going from one
extreme to another.'
The problem is that many of these policies, including an anti-monopoly
policy and an industrial policy of selective support for industry, have been
proclaimed by the government for a year or more. Nor are they inconsistent
with what Mr Fyodorov was trying to achieve in his role as finance minister.
They have not worked because they have been badly handled, insufficiently
developed or too awkward politically. Russia's economic reform has never
been comprehensive or synchronised. It has suffered from frequent personnel
changes and a dearth of talented people, in an area where pushing through
consistent policies places heavy demands on individual politicians and
economists.
Over the past year, Mr Fyodorov has struggled to curb Russia's high
inflation, and has, at the least, fended off a real threat of
hyperinflation. In the process, he was accused of starving various
ministries of funds to spend on industry, defence, and other state sectors.
But he had little choice in a government accustomed to taking spending
decisions it could not afford.
Mr Fyodorov's departure does not mean the death of economic reform; that is
a process difficult to stop. But it heralds a slowing of pace, and the loss
of a highly effective professional to a government where no ministers,
except Mr Anatoly Chubais, the deputy prime minister responsible for
privatisation, can point to concrete achievements. 'One wonders whether
they'll be any more successful in picking industrial winners than losers,
especially given a populist parliament,' one economist said.
Mr Fyodorov's departure will be a blow to the confidence of western
financial institutions, creditor banks, and large sections of Russia's
business community. He was the man people loved to hate, but many of his
supposed enemies will be sorry to see him go, for, at the least, he pursued
a clear policy rather than no policy at all. 'He was right not to give money
to everybody who wanted it,' said one executive at Avtovaz, Russia's biggest
car producer. 'Why should he give more money to agriculture when we cannot
even reap what we sow?'
</TEXT>
