<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JAN 94 / 'Granny' bond draws a mixed response
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An interest rate of 7 per cent gross fixed for five years was offered to
people of 65 and over by the government yesterday with the launch of the new
Pensioners' Guaranteed Income Bond from National Savings.
The bond, which goes on sale from today, will require a minimum deposit of
Pounds 500 and has a maximum of Pounds 20,000. Interest will be paid
monthly.
Though it is a five-year investment, investors will be able to withdraw
their money before then, provided that they give two months' notice and
suffer the loss of two months' interest.
Building societies yesterday expressed a mixture of relief and reservations
at the details of the bond, which has concerned them since Mr Kenneth
Clarke, the chancellor, announced it in the November Budget.
Banks and societies' five-year fixed rate bonds giving monthly interest
offer a variety of rates depending on conditions and deposit size, with many
in the 5 to 6 per cent gross range.
Mr John Wriglesworth, societies analyst at UBS, said: 'This will definitely
be tough competition for societies. There are a lot of outstanding balances
at risk.'
But most societies are unlikely to rush into revising their products until
the scale of the movement of deposits becomes clearer.
Halifax said the interest rate was not as attractive as it had expected, but
the maximum investment was higher than anticipated.
Mr Andrew Longhurst, chief executive of Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester, said the
bond forced pensioners to take a view on interest rate movements.
</TEXT>
