<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / The FT500 (25): Edging towards a place in the top 500 -
Already the Czech republic has two companies ripe for inclusion among
Europe's giants. Meanwhile, mass privatisation should take off in Poland
this year / Country Analyses - Eastern Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A combination of privatisation on an unprecedented scale and the stock
market surges which spread from Warsaw to Prague and Budapest in the second
half of last year has brought to the fore a growing number of private
central European companies ripe for inclusion in the FT500.
Already the Czech republic boasts two companies whose market capitalisation
at the end of the year exceeded that of the Dollars 921m recorded by the
Finnish company at the bottom of the FT500. What is more, the Dollars 2.7bn
capitalisation of CEZ, the electrical utility company which heads the Czech
list, equals the total year-end market capitalisation of the 22 stocks
quoted on the Warsaw stock exchange. Total Polish capitalisation reached
Dollars 2.7bn after a hectic year in which Polish-quoted share prices rose
on average by 700 per cent.
Both Prague and Warsaw outclassed the Budapest stock exchange where the
market capitalisation of the 28 quoted shares ended the year at Dollars 820m
after a late rally which boosted the Budapest index by 50 per cent over the
last few weeks but still left shares languishing in real terms below their
values of two years ago.
Pre-war Czechoslovakia boasted one of the most developed industrial
economies in the world. It lost competitiveness and was diverted into
inappropriate energy and raw material consuming heavy industry under Soviet
domination. But the innate strengths of the Czech economy and the underlying
resources of a skilled labour force are once again coming to the surface
under the single-mindedly pro-market and pro-privatisation policies of the
government led by Mr Vaclav Klaus.
The Czechs pioneered mass privatisation, with more than 1,300 enterprises
privatised in the first round of privatisation through vouchers and over 800
enterprises about to be privatised under the second round.
More than 70 per cent of the 8m Czech citizens who paid around Dollars 30
for vouchers permitting them to buy shares in the 1,300 companies with a
book value vastly in excess of the vouchers, deposited them with the private
investment funds which sprang up to manage the deluge of new shares and new
shareholders.
In effect most voucher holders have become shareholders in the funds who
actually manage the shares, buying and selling on and off the stock exchange
and building up controlling packets of shares where possible.
A glance at the top six shares quoted on the Prague stock exchange is
instructive. After CEZ comes Ceska Sporitelna, the Czech savings bank,
capitalised at Dollars 1.06bn, which is followed by the biggest commercial
bank, Komercni Banka at Dollars 900m. The Czech banks are all in the throes
of bad-debt write-offs and capital re-financing to fit them for their future
role as financiers of the emerging small and medium private business sector.
The two biggest quoted companies after CEZ and the banks are both
majority-controlled by foreign investors. Tabak, the former state tobacco
monopoly bought by Philip Morris, is capitalised at Dollars 695m while
Cokoladovny, controlled by Nestle, pitches in at Dollars 648m. Way behind in
sixth place comes the country's largest engineering group, Skoda Pilzen,
which is capitalised at Dollars 320m. Skoda Automobilovna, the motor car
company which is the largest and probably best known Czech company, is in
the throes of becoming controlled 70 per cent by Volkswagen, with the state
retaining the remaining shares, so it is not a quoted company.
The relatively slow, case by case, privatisation approach decided on by the
Hungarian authorities, with the emphasis on trade sales to foreign
investors, has paid off to the extent that Hungary has attracted the bulk of
the more than Dollars 5.5bn invested in central and eastern Europe over the
past three years. But the reluctance to embrace mass privatisation is
reflected in the relative smallness of the Budapest stock exchange with only
28 shares quoted, of which the most sought after are those of Fotex, the
photographic and luxury goods company. Last year, turnover in shares at
18.26bn forints was only 10 per cent of total stock exchange turnover which
was dominated by trading in government bonds and treasury bills.
In Poland the biggest company by market capitalisation is Wedel, the
chocolatemaker now controlled by Pepsico as part of its ambitious foray, in
competition with Coca Cola, into the biggest market of the region. Poland
has 39m people compared to just over 10m each in Hungary and the Czech
republic, 5m in Slovakia and under 2m in Slovenia whose own fledgling stock
exchange is tipped to come alive in 1994 as the well-run economy picks up.
Wedel, capitalised at Dollars 304m as of end-September, is followed on the
Warsaw stock exchange, housed in the former offices of the Communist party
central committee building, by Elektrim, the former state power and
telecommunications equipment trading company at Dollars 214m. Fast expanding
Elektrim is among several quoted companies planning to tap the market this
year by raising fresh equity, in Elektrim's case by partially floating off
several of its subsidiary companies.
Mass privatisation should take off in Poland this year as the new left of
centre government carries on the previous government's plan to privatise up
to 500 state-controlled enterprises and create 20-30 so-called 'National
Investment Funds' with foreign and Polish managers to perform the vital
functions of modernising, slimming down, restructuring and eventually
re-financing their companies.
This process is expected to greatly expand the stock exchange listings over
the rest of this decade. The new government is so keen to raise revenue by
successful privatisation that it appears unlikely to impose new taxes on
capital gains or tax share transactions as demanded by some of its more
orthodox left-wing supporters.
The recent successful stock market debut of the first two privatised banks,
the Wielkopolski and Slaski banks, has already expanded the number of
shareholders in Poland to more than 200,000, and last year's boom has
whetted the appetite of many more potential investors in a country where
real incomes, and savings, are rising after 4 per cent GDP growth last year.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
TOP 10 POLISH COMPANIES BY MARKET CAPITALISATION*
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
