<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / The FT500 (23): Devaluation helps Swedes and Finns -
Recession continued to dog the region but stock markets rose sharply as
interest rates fell and signs of recovery began to show / Country Analyses -
Nordic Region
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HUGH CARNEGY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
After a dismal, recession-driven slump in the rankings in 1992, Nordic
companies have rebounded significantly this year.
Ten new Nordic entries - or re-entries - outweighed five departures (two of
which were due to takeovers), compared with a net loss last year of 11. The
turnaround took the total of Swedish, Danish, Finnish and Norwegian
companies in the list to 45.
Nordic companies also made their presence felt among the more eye-catching
performers. Skandinaviska Enskilda Banken, Sweden's leading commercial bank,
vaulted back from a loss-driven share collapse to re-enter the top 500 at
number 199. Its rival Svenska Handelsbanken topped the list of big risers
among established FT500 companies by surging from 465th place to 223rd.
Astra, the Swedish pharmaceutical group, held its 1992 ranking of 32, the
highest of any Nordic company. It also ranked as Europe's seventh most
profitable company, with a 49.8 per cent return on capital.
Another prominent Nordic re-entry to the FT500 was Nokia, the Finnish
telecommunications group, which is riding a tide of growth in its mobile
telephone division. It came in at number 301. Meanwhile, Norsk Hydro, the
petroleum and fertiliser group that is Norway's biggest stock-listed
company, registered Europe's biggest increase in profits, showing a rise of
no less than 7,715 per cent.
Recession continued to dog the Nordic region in 1993 - especially in Sweden
and Finland. But stock markets in the four countries rose sharply as
interest rates fell and signs of recovery began to show in the latter part
of the year. In Sweden and Finland, companies also benefited greatly from
the big devaluations in the Swedish krona and Finnish markka over the year,
which boosted profitability.
Finland's representation in the FT500 was quadrupled to eight from 1992,
reflecting a near doubling of values on the Helsinki stock exchange over the
year.
The top Finnish company, forestry and engineering group Repola, improved
from 387th place to 255th. Finnish newcomers, apart from Nokia, were
forestry groups Enso-Gutzeit and Metsa-Serla, respectively at 387 and 471;
Outokumpu, the mining company, at 482; and the banks Unitas and
Kansallis-Osake-Pankki. Unitas came in at 440, while KOP edges in at 500.
Six of Denmark's 10 FT500 companies also improved their positions. The main
reverse was Carlsberg, the brewer, which was toppled from Danish top spot as
it slid from 158th place overall to 229th. It was overtaken by AP Moller,
the shipping group, whose joint parent companies, D/S Svendborg and D/S af
1912, moved up to 148 and 149 on the overall list respectively.
Closer inspection of the rankings, however, reveals that stock market
performance tended to be well ahead of bottom-line performance. Eleven of
the 25 European companies showing the biggest swings from profit to loss
were Swedish, Finnish or Danish.
Prominent among these were banks and insurance companies. Most of the
region's financial stocks rebounded strongly in 1993, as banks and insurance
groups took the first steps back to health after crippling loan losses in
1992. But they are still carrying the burden of those losses: Unitas
suffered Europe's 12th biggest swing to loss from profit  - Dollars 445.5m.
Others in the list of crashing profits were Swedish insurers Trygg-Hansa SPP
and Skandia, S-E Banken, Den Danske Bank and Unidanmark.
Traditional Swedish industrial powerhouses also put up a mixed showing, at
best. Three Swedish industrial departures from the FT500 - Trelleborg, the
troubled mining and metals group; Industrivarden, a mixed investment group;
and Korsnas, a pulp and paper company taken over by Kinnevik - balanced new
financial sector entries S-E Banken, Skandia and Trygg-Hansa SPP, to leave
Sweden's total representation at 21. Of these, only seven improved their
rankings.
Volvo's tumultuous year - which swung from heavy losses and an agreement to
merge with France's Renault, to resurgent profits and the controversial
breaking of the merger deal - left it down slightly in the rankings, from
129th place to 136th.
