<PROFILE>_AN-EATCKAGKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940120
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / London Stock Exchange: Tesco cheer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, JOEL KIBAZO, PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A rare piece of good news for the food retail sector came in the form of a
trading statement from Tesco, which was well received by the market and sent
the shares forward 15 to 251 1/2 p in hefty trading of 18m.
Food analysts said the supermarket group's decision to cut its capital
expenditure and store opening programme eased concern over market
saturation. They were also cheered by the decision to increase the dividend
ahead of earnings growth. 'Tesco has at last faced reality with this
statement,' said one specialist.
As widely rumoured, the supermarket group decided to begin making provisions
for depreciating its buildings and also to make a write-down of Pounds 85m
on surplus land.
The positive sentiment, together with the rising market, helped the other
retailers. Among these, J. Sainsbury climbed 10 to 477p.
Strong two-way business in Rolls-Royce saw turnover jump to 18m as US buyers
returned to the stock, ignoring a profits downgrade from Hoare Govett, the
group's broker.
However, there were fears that the renewed US interest may soon challenge
the 29.5 per cent limit on overseas ownership set in the group's articles of
association.
Hoare reduced its current year forecast by Pounds 10m to Pounds 75m. The
shares firmed 1 1/2 to 174p.
British Aerospace was back in favour on hopes of a lucrative Hawk order from
India, and a view that the recent falls had been overdone. The shares
bounced 25 to 416p, with volume reaching 7.5m.
The Pacific Rim-influenced bank stocks, principally HSBC and Standard
Chartered, continued to race ahead, boosted by the latest rise on the Hong
Kong market.
Standard was 26 higher at 1229p, after reaching 1248p, after Cazenove, the
bank's broker, was said to have given the stock a strong push, highlighting
the discrepancy between Standard's prospective price/earnings ratio, around
the 7.5 mark, compared with that of HSBC, some 10.5 times, and other Far
Eastern stocks which are rated around 20 times earnings. Some of the
market's super optimists are forecasting a doubling of Standard's share
price.
HSBC added 29 at 976p. Bank of East Asia is not a subsidiary of HSBC, as
incorrectly reported here yesterday.
TSB rose 10 to a record 286p as a number of broking firms continued to
upgrade their estimates and recommendations on the stock following the
recent preliminary figures.
Oil issues were restrained by worries about crude oil prices, but were also
said to have been held back by hints that Enterprise and Lasmo are about to
have their debt ratings reduced by Standard &amp; Poor's, one of the leading US
credit-rating agencies.
Enterprise retained a 7 gain at 469p, still helped by stories that
Elf-Aquitaine has decided not to sell its 10 per cent stake in the short
term. Lasmo edged up 2 1/2 to 126 1/2 p following news that its important
Indonesian oil equivalent reserves have been upgraded by 13 per cent, or 59m
barrels of oil equivalent, following an independent assessment.
BAA lost 4 to 1056p on fears that a review on airport regulation announced
on Tuesday may have a negative impact on BAA's pricing formula discussions
with the government due to start later this year.
In a strong property sector, MEPC was further boosted by a positive annual
meeting and the shares jumped 29 to 561p.
Some leading leisure stocks were knocked, with Forte declining 5 to 276p.
Kleinwort Benson, which has Forte as a 'hold', said the stock was overbought
in the face of the hesitant pace of recovery in the hotel market.
Turnover in Burton hit 16m as Lehman Brothers matched a buyer and seller of
6.5m shares. The deals were struck at 73p and 73 3/4 p. The stock nudged up
a half-penny to 74p.
</TEXT>
