<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Record close as weak earnings
news ignored
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US equities jumped to new highs just before the close yesterday, shrugging
off a string of weak earnings reports which had earlier dragged down share
prices, writes Richard Waters in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average see-sawed during the day before ending at a
record peak of 3,884.37 for a net rise of 14.08. It had briefly reached this
level in mid-morning, before poor 1993 results from a number of companies
knocked it down nearly 20 points.
The market recovered briefly after lunchtime with the release of the Federal
Reserve's 'Beige Book', which reported an acceleration of economic growth in
some sectors, and the more positive tone continued through to the close. The
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 followed a similar pattern, finishing 0.05 up at
474.30. Trading volume on the New York SE amounted to 311.4m shares.
Computer and drugs stocks led the slide during the morning as leading
companies in both sectors reported poor results, while banking issues
continued the sell-off which has followed a recent run-up in share prices.
The bad news for computer issues was delivered by Intel, the electronic chip
maker, which announced figures after the markets had closed on Tuesday, and
Digital Equipment, which reported a loss of 53 cents a share in its most
recent quarter and cautioned about the outlook for the first half of 1994.
Digital dropped Dollars 3 5/8 to Dollars 32 3/4 on 2.84m shares traded and
Intel surrendered Dollars 4 3/4 to Dollars 62 1/2 .
The weakness in technology stocks helped to depress the Nasdaq stock index,
which has a higher weighting towards technology companies. The index had
lost 3.74 at 789.28 by the close, down from a record peak the previous day.
Drugs shares were battered after Pfizer, seen as one of the stars of the
industry, reported a marked slowdown in sales in the final three months of
1993. The stock plunged Dollars 5 to Dollars 62 7/8 on the day, in the
process dragging down other pharmaceutical issues. Among the industry
leaders, Merck shed Dollars  5/8 to Dollars 35 7/8 and Bristol-Myers Squibb
Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 58 3/4 . Schering-Plough was among the biggest
losers, falling Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars 64 3/8 .
Leading banks continued the retreat which has followed a strong results
season. Citicorp, in spite of its recent strong earnings news, lost Dollars
1 to Dollars 40 1/4 . BankAmerica, the only leading bank to announce figures
yesterday, dipped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 46 5/8 , as the US's second
largest bank continued to feel the effects of the weak Californian economy.
BancOne fell Dollars 1 1/4 on heavy trading of 3.36m shares on an analyst's
report that its earnings will come under pressure, taking it to Dollars 35
5/8 , around its low for the past 12 months.
Canada
Toronto stocks finished on a mixed note but the TSE 300 index managed a
sixth consecutive all-time closing peak, gaining 1.0 at 4,562.9, after
touching 4,574.3 during the session. Volume was a brisk 96m shares valued at
CDollars 1.3bn.
Strong pipeline, energy and media stocks were offset by sagging gold and
banking issues hit by profit-taking.
</TEXT>
