<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / International Company News: Shares slide as Digital
Equipment disappoints
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Digital Equipment fell sharply yesterday when the troubled US
computer manufacturer reported a second-quarter net loss of Dollars 72.1m -
far worse than Wall Street had expected - and a 12 per cent drop in
operating revenues.
The red ink, which worked through at 53 cents a share, was little changed
from the loss of Dollars 73.8m, or 57 cents a share, reported in the same
period of last year. Analysts had been looking for earnings close to
break-even.
Digital's shares closed at Dollars 32 3/4 , down Dollars 3 5/8 , on the New
York Stock Exchange.
Digital, like International Business Machines, has been struggling to come
to grips with fundamental changes in the computer market. These have shifted
demand away from its mini-computers to networks of much cheaper personal
computers, and workstations, using 'open systems' rather than proprietary
software.
Mr Robert Palmer, chief executive since July 1992, is overseeing a
restructuring programme which has had mixed results: a return to profits in
the three months to last June, followed by worse-than-expected losses in
each of the last two quarters.
Mr Palmer, expressing dissatisfaction with last quarter's revenues and loss,
said Digital continued to work to lower its costs, stabilise and then
improve revenues.
'It took several years for the company to get into this situation, and it is
taking some time for us to restore profitability and growth,' he said.
The revenue decline was attributed mainly to a continued drop in demand for
the company's larger VAX computer systems. The company said its personal
computer business continued to double in units, year-over-year, and showed
strong double-digit revenue growth.
The results were hit by unfavourable foreign currency movements, weakness in
the European and US economies, and a decline in product margins, due to a
shift in the mix of sales to products with lower profits, such as personal
computers.
For the six months to January 1, Digital reported a net loss of Dollars
155.3m, or Dollars 1.15 a share, compared with a loss of Dollars 334.4m, or
Dollars 2.60 a share, last time.
Intel results, Page 26
</TEXT>
