<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Kita takes the blame for Hanwa's big losses: The Japanese
group's withdrawal from speculation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO and WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Shigeru Kita has resigned as president of Hanwa, the Japanese steel
trading company, taking responsibility for huge investment losses in
financial markets.
The losses, blamed on the sharp fall in the Tokyo stock market, will result
in an extraordinary write-off of Y120bn (Pounds 720m) this year and an
after-tax loss forecast at Y47.2bn. This is believed to be one of the
largest write-offs related to financial transactions made by any Japanese
company.
Hanwa said the Y1,300bn funds still invested in financial instruments would
be withdrawn over three to four years, as it ceased all transactions aimed
at making profits on the financial markets. It would instead concentrate on
its core business of trading in steel and other products.
The decision by Hanwa, whose enormous influence on the financial markets at
one time earned it the nickname of 'shadow Bank of Japan', came as a stark
reminder of the damage wrought by speculative financial trading.
In particular, the resignation of Mr Kita, who will become a consultant to
the company, marks a humiliating end for a man whose keen financial instinct
once brought the company power and wealth. At its peak, speculative
financial trading, known as zaitech, supported record annual pre-tax profits
of Y38.4bn, of which more than 70 per cent came from non-operating profits.
Mr Kita will be succeeded initially by his elder brother, Mr Jiro Kita, who
is chairman. Mr Jiro Kita will resign both posts when his son, Mr Shuji
Kita, a former bureaucrat with the Ministry of International Trade and
Industry and managing director of Hanwa, assumes the helm in the near
future.
Mr Takashi Iwami, vice-president, said the company's core business of
trading in specialised steel products was firm, leaving its sales estimate
unchanged at Y570bn.
However, pre-tax profits would be Y11.7bn instead of the previously expected
Y4bn as losses from financial transactions would no longer arise at the
pre-tax level. The final dividend is being passed.
</TEXT>
<XX>
