<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Mid 250 driven to new peak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The FT-SE Mid 250 Index, covering medium-sized companies on the London stock
market, was driven to a new peak yesterday by heavy options-related buying,
estimated at up to Pounds 1bn.
The sight of the Mid 250 leaping forward 135.5 to 4,148.8 helped drive the
FT-SE 100 Index of the UK's most highly valued companies to a new closing
peak of 3,475.1, up 38.1 points.
Senior traders said UBS, the Swiss-owned securities house, had been buying
Mid 250 stocks ferociously since the end of last week, ahead of the issue of
a large covered warrant on the index. A warrant is a derivative instrument
which allows investors to exercise an option to buy the underlying shares at
the price on the day of purchase.
Dealers believed that word of the strategy leaked into the London market
yesterday morning, prompting rival dealers to mark up share prices, and
triggering a rush of buying by UBS in the afternoon as it sought to complete
its order.
The head trader at a leading UK securities house commented: 'It's been an
opportunity to lose a fortune - you couldn't buy anything for love nor
money. This is the latest in a chain of events pointing to the increasing
importance of derivatives and other instruments.'
UBS was said to have been keen to carry out the deal ahead of the February 4
launch of OMLX, a London-based equity derivatives exchange which plans to
deal in Mid 250 contracts.
SG Warburg Securities and NatWest Securities were also said to have been
active.
</TEXT>
