<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Quake damage may hit Dollars 30bn: Clinton pledges federal
aid as he tours devastated areas of LA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LOS ANGELES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
As President Bill Clinton toured devastated areas of Los Angeles yesterday,
damage estimates from Monday's earthquake rose as high as Dollars 30bn
(Pounds 20.2bn) - making it the most costly disaster in US history.
Mr Clinton, who was met by a sharp after-shock as he surveyed a collapsed
freeway bridge, promised 'unusual and unprecedented' federal relief funds,
including an initial, immediate payment of Dollars 45m for highway repairs
and Dollars 239m in low interest loans to small businesses.
After talking to groups of residents gathered along his route through some
of the most badly hit areas of the San Fernando Valley, the president
addressed officials and residents at the Burbank airport.
Earlier yesterday, California's Governor, Mr Pete Wilson, told the Federal
Emergency Management Agency that the total cost of the quake could be
anywhere between Dollars 15bn and Dollars 30bn. His figures were in part
derived from estimates provided to the state by EQE International, a San
Francisco engineering consultancy firm that specialises in assessing natural
disaster risks.
Mr Earl Aurelius, vice-president of EQE, said the preliminary estimate of
damage was Dollars 15.1bn, excluding business losses. Of that, he estimated
that between Dollars 1.5bn and Dollars 1.9bn was covered by insurance.
EQE has used a computer model, combined with the observations of 30 of its
engineers, to assess the damage. 'We are feeling increasingly comfortable
with our Dollars 15.1bn estimate as we get further reports from the field,'
Mr Aurelius said.
Damage was far more serious than in the 1989 San Francisco bay area
earthquake, where costs rose to Dollars 7bn, because of the higher
concentration of properties near the epicentre, he said.
A spokesman for the governor said the estimates were preliminary, but the
Dollars 15bn to Dollars 30bn estimate provided a good 'ballpark'.
Although severe damage is limited to the western and north western parts of
the city, it is nonetheless overwhelming. The Federal Emergency Management
Agency said it expected to spend at least Dollars 1bn on repairs. The
California Transportation Department says repairs to freeways will cost at
least Dollars 100m, an estimate that is expected to double or triple as more
structural damage is revealed. Whatever the cost, it will take time -
probably years - to undo what the forces of nature accomplished in less than
a minute. On Tuesday, crews began demolishing quake-torn overpasses on the
Santa Monica and Golden State freeways. Working around the clock, they hope
to have the structures down in about a week. Rebuilding will take about a
year.
Workers also struggled yesterday to mend the San Fernando Valley's wrecked
aqueducts as water in the lone reservoir serving the area dwindled. Ruptured
aqueducts have cut off much of the water supply to the 260-square-mile
suburban expanse hardest hit by the quake.
Californian dream turns to nightmare, Page 6
Buildings that take quakes in their stride, Page 16
</TEXT>
