<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Observer: Risky business
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Dashiell Hammett must be spinning in his grave. Preventing Homicide in the
Workplace, published by the US National Institute for Occupational Safety
and Health, has demolished the myth that being a gumshoe is the world's most
dangerous profession. Taxi drivers run the greatest risk of being murdered
at work. Between 1980 and 1989 the average annual murder rate of cab drivers
was 27 in 100,000; most were shot. The next most perilous jobs were liquor
store workers and petrol station attendants. Private detectives came a
rather lame fourth.
</TEXT>
