<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Judging by last week's opening episode, Big Science is yet another attempt
to make science simple. The trouble is that ideas such as the Big Bang
theory aren't simple, and however slick your presentation, and sexy your
presenters, they are never going to become simple. Today, like every other
series, this one visits the US. Subjects include the Gaia theory and
neutrinos: where are they? (8.00 BBC2).
Minder, a survivor from the old days before franchise auctions spoiled
British commercial television, provides a rare oasis of high quality
entertainment in the desert of shoddiness that is ITV today. This week
brings the 100th episode. George Cole in the Arthur Daley role, without whom
everything would collapse, is involved with a friend who is fleeing a
murderer, and also with the Salvation Army (8.30).
Footage of a British wildcat hunting (not a feral cat but the real thing as
still found in the wilds of Scotland) is promised by Wildlife On One (8.30
BBC1). Great Railway Journeys travels across South Africa, visiting, among
other cities, Johannesburg (9.00 BBC2).
