<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Legal oddities in line for abolition
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
One of the strongest arguments for the government's drive against red tape
is the sheer oddity of some of the regulations being abolished.
For example, methylated spirits cannot be sold between 10pm on Saturday and
8am on Monday. Meths drinking, the Department of Trade and Industry says, is
a thing of the past, so legislation enacted 105 years ago can be repealed.
Scottish hairdressers are not allowed to open on Sunday. English haircuts on
the Sabbath are apparently legal.
Shops need a specific licence for selling kettle de-scaler. It is classed as
a poison.
The two government establishments which test gun barrels, in London and
Birmingham, have to ask permission from ministers if they want to raise
their prices. Since they are required to be non-profit making, the DTI
evidently thinks Mr Heseltine has better things to do.
Women in Scotland are not allowed to work in slaughterhouses. English women
are apparently more robust.
But some curious regulations which Lord Sainsbury's task force wanted
abolished are apparently to stay. Tobacconists must still display a warning
about health risks measuring not less than A3 size (it used to be A4). And
the law which states that betting offices are not allowed to have fruit
machines will probably stay, says the Home Office.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9651 Regulation of Miscellaneous Commercial Sectors.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 9
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT941-14497</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EATCKACVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940120
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Contracting-out curbs will go
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Obstacles to contracting out public services in central and local government
will be swept away as part of the de-regulation bill.
Ministers, civil servants and local authority officers will be able to pass
their legal responsibilities on to contractors. They will also be able to
hand over confidential information to contractors, who would be bound to
maintain confidentiality.
At present many public functions cannot be passed on to private-sector
contractors - including the payment of civil service pensions.
The de-regulation bill will allow a wide range of functions to be fully
contracted out, including company registration, local tax collection, the
registration of patents and the collection of business statistics.
The bill includes a new power for ministers to remove obstacles to
contracting-out, subject to a parliamentary vote to confirm their removal.
This procedure could not be used for functions that affect the liberty of
the individual or that involve entry, search and seizure powers.
</TEXT>
