<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / London truck ban to be simplified
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Measures to simplify a ban on trucks using many London roads at night and at
weekends were announced yesterday as part of the de-regulation initiative.
The Department of Transport also announced plans to replace the nationwide
system of bus and lorry operators' licences, which have a maximum life of
five years, with continuous licences.
Mr Steven Norris, transport minister responsible for London, said the permit
system in the capital would be abolished but heavy trucks would still have
to keep to main roads.
Abolition of permits, required by trucks which need to leave approved main
routes, will save road hauliers Pounds 3m a year. Restrictions on trucks of
16.5 tonnes and more using London's roads were introduced in January 1986 by
the Greater London Council.
The move from five-year vehicle operator licences to continuous licensing
will save businesses about Pounds 2.6m. Quality criteria will not be
changed, however, and periodic reviews of operators will still be made.
</TEXT>
