<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Car-boot sale move 'a crooks' charter'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government plans to remove restrictions on organisers of markets, fairs and
car-boot sales could cost millions of pounds and push up council tax bills,
according to the Labour-controlled Association of Metropolitan Authorities,
John Willman and David Owen write.
They could also amount to a 'crooks' charter', according to the Labour
party, making it harder to restrict car-boot sales.
'It is now widely recognised that a lot of burglars use car-boot sales as a
means of reselling what they steal,' said Mr Doug Henderson, shadow local
government minister.
Currently, local authorities which run franchise markets or fairs can stop
competitors holding events within a radius of 6 2/3 miles of their own
market. The de-regulation bill includes clauses to abolish these common-law
market franchise rights, which produce Pounds 110m a year in gross rental
for local authorities.
