<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Building society law up for review: Treasury to examine
rules on mergers, takeovers and changes of status
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A full review of the Building Societies Act, which sets out the regulatory
regime for societies, is to be undertaken by the government as part of the
de-regulation initiative.
The Treasury is expected to announce today that, together with the Building
Societies Commission, the sector's statutory regulator, it is to look again
at the provisions which have governed the activities of societies since
1986. The Building Societies Association will also be involved.
Areas which will be open for discussion will include the present limit of 40
per cent on funds which societies can raise on the wholesale markets, and
the merger and takeover procedures for societies. The process for societies
which change their status, as Abbey National did, will also be reviewed.
Some of the larger societies want greater access to wholesale funds, where
borrowing is cheaper, so that they can offer more attractive deals to
potential borrowers. Competition in this area is intense, and societies have
been losing market share to the banks.
'The financial services sector has changed considerably since the building
societies legislation was passed seven years ago,' one industry expert said,
'and the regulation ought to reflect that.'
The first tranche of the review is expected to end by early summer. The
govern-ment hopes to complete the process by the end of this year, perhaps
after further consultation in the autumn.
On this timescale, the conclusions would be ready soon after the time by
which the de-regulation bill should have become law. They could thus be
early candidates for the use of the new powers in the bill, which enable
ministers to amend primary legislation through orders.
The wider review complements the more technical changes affecting building
societies which are included in the de-regulation bill as well as in the
conclusions of the task force which advised the Department of Trade and
Industry on de-regulation in the financial services sector.
The de-regulation bill itself contains two new powers for societies.
First, they would be able to lend to a borrower against land held by a third
party. This would mean, for example, that when a borrower has negative
equity in his or her own house, a society could, for example, use the
borrower's parents' house as additional security.
Second, they would be allowed to take a direct part in syndicated lending,
with the removal of the existing restriction that means they can do so only
through subsidiary 'lending societies' prescribed by the regulator.
Other measures which are likely to follow include a streamlining of the
procedures determining how societies notify and consult their millions of
members about their activities.
Another technical change - in the way in which societies' permanent
interest-bearing shares and subordinate debt are classified - would give a
limited amount of greater flexibility in terms of the societies' wholesale
funding limits, even without any change in the overall limit.
</TEXT>
<XX>
