<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / MPs attack powers given to ministers: De-regulation bill
will make it easier to repeal laws - Employers will be able to 'override
agreements' on job shedding
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MPs yesterday hit out at the powers the bill will give ministers to repeal
regulatory measures without primary legislation. They also questioned
parliament's ability to subject the government's actions to adequate
scrutiny.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said Labour would resist
the government's attempt to take the power to overturn acts of parliament by
order of ministers.
'These laws were passed . . . to improve safety at work and to give the
consumer a fair deal,' he said. 'They should not be torn up without the same
full parliamentary process.'
Mr Nigel Griffiths, Labour's consumer spokesman, said the bill gave
ministers 'staggering' powers to 'axe' legislation and bypass the floor of
the House of Commons.
Mr Malcolm Bruce, Liberal Democrat trade and industry spokesman, said
parliament's role would be 'drastically reduced'.
Mr Bob Cryer, Labour chairman of the Commons statutory instruments
committee, said it was 'a bit rich' for the government to say it was
removing regulations by giving ministers' powers to make more.
The scrutiny of delegated powers was 'not adequate in parliament at the
moment', Mr Cryer said, predicting that the bill would make matters worse by
adding to the 'tidal wave' of regulations the government was producing.
Under scrutiny procedures set down in the bill ministers would have a duty
to consult those likely to be affected by a proposal before making an order
to put it into effect.
They would then be required to lay a draft order before parliament, with an
explanatory document setting out the reasons for the measure and other
details.
Forty days would have to elapse before the final order was submitted for
debate and approval in both houses of parliament.
Pressure on parliamentary time is such that it is usual for orders and
statutory instruments to be debated in the obscurity of a Westminster
committee-room rather than the main debating chamber. It is also common
practice for them subsequently to be nodded through rather than going to a
formal vote.
But mechanisms do exist for MPs to force both a debate on the floor of the
House and a formal vote where the issue is deemed serious or controversial
enough to warrant it. Once submitted, however, orders cannot be amended in
the way that bills can be.
According to the government the interim 40 days would provide an opportunity
for additional parliamentary scrutiny. It suggested yesterday that this
might be undertaken by new scrutiny committees, with powers to question
witnesses, in both the Commons and the Lords.
Under the government's suggestion it would be 'appropriate' for these
committees to be able to recommend either that a proposal should not proceed
in the way intended or that it should go ahead only if amended.
Ministers acknowledge that the final decision on what form parliamentary
scrutiny should take rests with the cross-party procedure committee.
Sir Peter Emery, the Conservative MP who chairs the committee, said
yesterday it would start considering the matter next week.
The bill states that ministers should 'have regard to' any representations
made during the period for parliamentary consideration.
</TEXT>
<XX>
