<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Small businesses greet red tape moves with muted applause
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's de-regulation bill was yesterday greeted with muted
applause by small-business groups which say the smallest companies spend a
disproportionate amount of time fighting red tape.
While welcoming the initiative, small-business lobby groups said it was
essential that the government followed through with a determined effort to
sweep away the red tape produced by centuries of legislation.
Businessmen and women were particularly pleased with the so-called small
business litmus test which would be applied by all departments when
introducing new legislation.
The departments would assess the costs of complying with new legislation by
consulting two or three typical small companies.
The DTI said it would adopt a 'think small' principle which meant new
regulations would be framed with small businesses in mind.
New legislation would be tested for its impact on small companies'
competitiveness and their ability to export, the cost of implementation and
practicality.
The CBI said the government was introducing a fundamental change in culture
and attitude. Officials should no longer see themselves as regulators but
de-regulators.
The Institute of Directors called the legislation 'a powerful antidote to
unnecessary and obstructive regulation'. Mr Peter Morgan, director- general
of the IOD, said: 'Until now it has been too easy for government to
introduce new laws and too difficult to get rid of them.
'Government and parliament will now have the the power to remove a noose
from the necks of business - they should use it.'
The IOD said the UK's high regulatory burden put British companies at a
disadvantage with competitors operating under more flexible regulatory
regimes.
The Forum of Private Business, which has 21,000 members, gave a cautious
welcome to the bill. Mr Stan Mendham, the forum's chief executive, said:
'Sadly we have seen many false starts on regulation.'
The success of the initiative depended on the government following through
its good intentions and resisting new legislation from the EU. 'To
understand the law, business owners need to read over 400,000 words and
complying with red tape costs 3 per cent of turnover,' said Mr Mendham. The
attack on red tape was 'too important for the economy to be allowed to
fail'.
The forum said its research showed a quarter of companies spent between five
and 10 hours a week complying with red tape.
Citing particularly absurd regulations, the British Chambers of Commerce
said it took five separate pieces of permission to set up a whelk stall. And
one EU directive included guidelines for the maximum permitted length and
curvature of cucumbers.
</TEXT>
