<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Barclays to pre-notify customers over charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Barclays Bank announced yesterday that it intends to introduce
pre-notification of charges on personal customers' accounts, a service all
banks are likely to be required to implement under a revised voluntary code
of practice.
The bank said no date had been set for introducing the service, which it
estimated would cost Pounds 12m a year. The service is already provided by
banks including National Westminster, and Lloyds has said it will be
introduced this year.
Pre-notification of charges is one of the likely changes to the code, which
is due to be revised from March. Changes are being drafted by a joint
working party of three groups representing banks and building societies.
The working party received recommendations from a review committee headed by
Sir George Blunden, former deputy governor of the Bank of England. But it is
thought to have decided independently to require pre-notification.
The working party - of the British Bankers Association, the Association of
Payment Clearing Services and the Building Societies Association - intends
to publish a draft of the code next month.
Although Barclays has publicly argued that it does not think most customers
want pre-notification of charges, the service was recommended in several
submissions to Sir George's committee from consumer groups and others.
The banks introduced the voluntary code in March 1992 after consumer
pressure over the quality of service. Barclays bank staff unions are
planning to ballot members on proposals for a one-day strike against job
cuts, Richard Donkin writes.
The strike, proposed for February or March, has been discussed between the
Barclays Group Staff Union and Bifu, the banking and insurance union.
Barclays announced last week it had increased its five-year job-cutting
programme by 3,000 to 21,000 over the next two years.
</TEXT>
