<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Number of references to MMC may drop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Merging companies are to be allowed to offer a wider range of undertakings
to the director-general of fair trading in an attempt to cut the number of
mergers referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission.
The proposal, outlined in the de-regulation bill yesterday, was one of the
measures designed to cut out unnecessary overlap in the roles of the Office
of Fair Trading and the MMC and to reduce the period of uncertainty for
companies caught up in competition investigations.
Instead of referring the merger to the MMC, ministers can now accept
undertakings from merging companies to dispose of parts of their business.
The bill would allow ministers to accept a wider range of undertakings, for
example on regulating the prices of certain goods of the merged business.
The government also proposes to allow companies to give undertakings as an
alternative to a monopoly reference to the MMC.
The OFT and other regulators are also to be allowed to accept undertakings
or ask the MMC to investigate an anti-competitive act under the 1980
Competition Act without carrying out a formal preliminary inquiry.
Lawyers said the measures should result in a change of culture at the OFT
and lead it into a dialogue with companies.
The bill also contains measures to reduce the burden on small businesses by
cutting the range of restrictive trade agreements which have to be notified
to the OFT. In a separate development yesterday the government announced
that from February 9 it was to raise the assets threshold above which
mergers qualify for review from Pounds 30m to Pounds 70m.
</TEXT>
