FT  20 JAN 94 / TUC condemns plans for redundancy selection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An unexpected provision in the government's de-regulation bill that will
allow companies to select employees for redundancy even if it contravenes
'customary arrangements' or 'agreed procedures' was condemned last night by
the trades union congress.
The proposed change in the law will end the hallowed industrial relations
principle of 'last in, first out'.
Mr Brendan Barber, the TUC's deputy general secretary, said: 'plans to make
it possible for employers to override agreements and to select who they wish
for redundancy is just another kick in the teeth for good industrial
relations.'
At present under the employment protection (consolidation act) 1978 any
employer who selects workers for redundancy could face a charge of 'unfair
dismissal' before an industrial tribunal. the government believes the
existing law is 'unnecessarily restrictive' and believes 'employers ought to
have flexibility to adapt to current circumstances'.
The government argues: 'employees' interests would still be protected
because in the event of a claim of unfair dismissal an industrial tribunal
would consider whether an employer had acted fairly in the circumstances.'
'The government's proposal
The bill will also enable the repeal of outdated health and safety
legislation subject to consultation with the health and safety commission.
A report on the benefits and costs of health and safety regulations by the
commission will be submitted to mr david hunt, the employment secretary, in
april.
Mr Frank Davies, the commission's chairman, said yesterday: 'I cannot
conceive the commission will recommend anything which will lower health and
safety standards overall nor could I believe the government would accept it
if we did.'
The bill also proposes that employment agencies will no longer have to be
licensed before starting up.
</TEXT>
