<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Retail activity was subdued over Christmas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A disappointing rise in Christmas retail sales, revealed in official figures
yesterday, indicated that consumer activity was more subdued than anecdotal
evidence from stores and shops suggests.
Last month the volume of sales fell a seasonally adjusted 0.2 per cent
compared with November, although it was 4 per cent higher than in December
1992. The year-on-year rate disappointed expectations for a 5.2 per cent
increase, particularly since sales in the previous Christmas period were
poor. Nonetheless, this was the biggest rise since July last year.
The news from the Central Statistical Office of the monthly fall in sales
came as a surprise following a report earlier this week from the
Confederation of British Industry, which painted a more upbeat picture of
the Christmas trading period.
Statisticians pointed out, however, that the CBI gave only the year-on-year
increase in sales, and that its figures were similar to the official series
on a month-on-month basis.
Anecdotal evidence of booming Christmas sales has further muddied the
picture, but this has come from the large chain stores which account for
two-thirds of retail sales. They are more easily able to hold down prices
and are therefore faring much better than smaller shops.
The most up-to-date figures confirm that on a year-on-year basis big
retailers are significantly outperforming small ones. The volume of sales by
small businesses in November fell 0.2 per cent compared with a year ago
while large retailers increased their sales by 5.8 per cent in the same
period.
The latest dip in retail sales may prompt unease in the government that
consumer spending will weaken significantly when Budget tax increases come
into effect in the spring. Viewed over three months, however, there is a
clear upward trend in volume of sales growth.
In the three months to December sales volume was 0.7 per cent higher then in
the previous three months, and 3.7 per cent up on the same period a year
earlier. Based on non-seasonally adjusted data, the average weekly value of
retail sales last month was Pounds 3.7bn, 5.9 per cent higher than in
December 1992.
The strongest growth in the latest three months has been in sales by mixed
businesses, a category that includes department stores. Sales volume was up
1.6 per cent in the three months to December compared with the previous
three months.
For food retailers and specialist non-food retailers the rises were 1 per
cent and 0.1 per cent respectively.
Figures released by CSO also show that sales volume was 3.6 per cent higher
last year than in 1992. This was the biggest increase since 1988 when the
increase, compared with 1987 was 6.2 per cent.
Consumers bought Pounds 5.4bn worth of goods and services using credit and
debit cards in December, according to the Credit Card Research Group, funded
by the credit card industry, Alison Smith writes.
Debit card spending was much higher at food and drinks retailers than credit
card spending, while the positions were reversed at gift stores.
</TEXT>
