<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / BAe to shed 500 more jobs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Aerospace yesterday unveiled plans for further job cuts involving
about 500 staff in its missile division, more than a tenth of its remaining
workforce in the sector.
The cuts, likely to involve compulsory redundancies, follow a reduction of
830 jobs at three civil aircraft plants announced last week.
The company's Dynamics guided-weapon division, which is due to be merged
with the missile-making activities of France's Matra group, will be reduced
to 4,040 employees, less than a quarter of the level at the end of the
1980s.
BAe blamed the cuts on deferment or cancellation of orders.
The main reduction affects 330 jobs at BAe's main missile manufacturing
operation at Lostock, near Bolton. Another 160 jobs will go at Stevenage in
Hertfordshire and 20 at Bristol.
The company said the cuts were not related to the merger talks with Matra.
Southampton warship builder Vosper Thornycroft announced yesterday it was
recruiting 60 employees, mainly steelworkers.
