<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / BAA backs new airline at Gatwick
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BAA, the airports operator, and British Aerospace are backing a proposal by
an Italian airline entrepreneur to start a European scheduled airline based
at London's Gatwick airport.
The new airline, Debonair, plans to operate up to seven jets from Gatwick to
European destinations including Paris, Amsterdam, Munich, Berlin, Rome,
Milan, Madrid, and Barcelona.
The airline is being set up by Mr Franco Mancassola, a former senior
executive with Continental Airlines and World Airways of the US, who has 30
years' experience in the international airline industry.
Mr Mancassola said yesterday he had already raised Pounds 6.5m of the Pounds
13m equity finance for his new airline and planned to launch Gatwick
scheduled services next autumn.
BAA supports the venture because it has the potential to fill the gap left
at Gatwick by the collapse of Air Europe and the demise of Dan-Air, which
has been absorbed by British Airways.
Mr Allan Munds, Gatwick airport's managing director, said passenger traffic
on European scheduled routes from Gatwick had fallen from 5.5m-3.5m in the
past three years.
With BA dominating short-haul European scheduled airline services from
Gatwick, Mr Munds said many long-haul airlines using the airport were keen
to see a new airline offering European services from Gatwick.
The government's liberalisation of London air traffic rules has encouraged
many international airlines to switch services from Gatwick to Heathrow,
which has become overcrowded.
Both BAA and the international carriers using Gatwick see a new entrant as
creating greater competition and choice at Gatwick.
The new airline plans to start services in September using four BAe 146
regional jets leased from British Aerospace. Mr Mancassola plans to increase
the fleet to seven by the summer of 1995.
Mr Robin Southwell, of BAe's asset management organisation, said the UK
manufacturer was backing the new venture and proposing to lease the first
four aircraft for a total of Dollars 500,000 a month.
Apart from daily scheduled services to European business cities, the new
airline plans weekend services to leisure centres including Nice and Venice.
</TEXT>
