<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Smith attacks Labour MP for appearing on Iraq TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, yesterday delivered a strong reprimand to
Mr George Galloway, Labour MP for Glasgow Hillhead, for appearing on Iraqi
television with President Saddam Hussein.
Mr Galloway, who has strongly opposed United Nations sanctions on Iraq, was
quoted as saying to Mr Saddam: 'Sir, allow me to salute your courage, power
and indefatigability. I would like you to know that we are with you until
Nasir (victory).'
Mr Smith issued a statement deploring 'foolish statements' made by Mr
Galloway. He said Mr Galloway would be interviewed by Mr Derek Foster, the
opposition chief whip, when he returned to the Commons.
Labour MPs speculated that the party might go as far as to 'withdraw the
whip' from Mr Galloway, preventing him from attending meetings of the
parliamentary Labour party and voting in backbench elections.
A prominent backbencher said sentiment was running high against Mr Galloway,
whose visit was 'unauthorised'.
However, Mr Galloway said his remarks had been misinterpreted. 'It was not
to Saddam Hussein, it was to allow me to salute the Iraqi people's courage,
power and indefatigability in the face of the enormous barrage of explosive
ordnance and strangulating blockade,' he said.
Mr Galloway sought to undermine criticism by linking his concern for
ordinary Iraqis with his long-standing opposition to British arms sales to
the Baghdad government.
The government moved quickly to exploit Labour's embarrassment, which
Conservative officials hope will help to deflect attention from Mr John
Major's troubled back to basics campaign.
Sir Norman Fowler, chairman of the Conservative party, said Mr Smith should
demand a full retraction from Mr Galloway, or expel him from the
parliamentary party.
A senior Labour official said no action would be taken against Mr Galloway
until a full inquiry had been completed.
</TEXT>
