<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Westminster council defence faces challenge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS, STEWART DALBY and PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The principal defence of the Westminster councillors, who were named by the
district auditor for alleged gerrymandering in the sale of council houses in
marginal wards, is challenged by documents obtained by the Financial Times.
Many of the councillors, including Dame Shirley Porter, former leader of the
council, have argued that they had received legal advice approving the sales
policy.
But a transcript of an interview by Mr John Magill, the district auditor, of
Mr Jeremy Sullivan, the barrister who advised Westminster city council on
its now-abandoned policy, which was conducted on November 12 1992, indicates
that had Mr Sullivan been fully briefed on the council's motives, he would
not have endorsed the policy.
Mr Sullivan believes he was not shown vital papers on the policy's effect on
the homeless.
Mr Magill has called Westminster council's policy 'disgraceful and improper'
and provisionally recommended that 10 councillors and officials be
surcharged Pounds 21.25m over their involvement in the affair.
In the transcript, Mr Magill puts the question in the following terms: ''The
majority party nearly lost the election, and since then they have been
talking about targeting marginal wards. We are collecting data on these
eight wards, we are talking about designating all the properties in those
eight wards' and that was the sort of background flavour, what is your view
of that?' Mr Sullivan replied: 'I would have said: 'It is unlawful.' If that
is the way it has been put.'
A letter from Mr Merv Montacute, the council's managing director, to Mr
Andrew Dismore, the council's Labour leader, indicates that Mr Sullivan did
not see the final draft of the reports drawn up by council officials for the
council's housing committee.
The letter also says: 'My understanding of the position is that Mr Sullivan
was not shown a list identifying specific properties for designation.'
Mr Sullivan did not see another key report - Westminster Housing and
Economic Study - which was commissioned by the council from PA Cambridge
Economic Consultants. The report made clear in 1987 that there was a serious
and worsening homeless problem in the area. It said: 'Housing problems for
the most vulnerable groups are getting worse, an impression confirmed by the
continuing high level of homelessness.'
This finding is crucial in the light of Mr Magill's provisional view that
the council's sales policy was 'inconsistent with the statutory duties which
the council owed to the homeless.
In his interview Mr Magill showed Mr Sullivan the two volumes of the report,
to discover if he had been asked to read it.
Mr Sullivan replied: 'I think I should have a fit if I had been asked to do
that. I certainly was not. I am not sure whether I have ever been asked to
read that, even in preparation for the judicial review proceedings.'
Mr Magill said in the public statement made last week: 'No local housing
authority acting reasonably would adopt a policy, the anticipated
consequences of which were that the number of homeless households placed in
temporary accommodation would increase by 172 each year and that the net
revenue costs to the council would increase by over Pounds 1.5m in each
succeeding year.'
</TEXT>
