<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / MoD offers contract deal to potential shipyard buyer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Ministry of Defence would be in a position to award a contract to Swan
Hunter, the stricken Tyneside shipyard, if a potential purchaser was willing
to underwrite the bid, it emerged yesterday.
Since Swans went into receivership in May the MoD has said the yard can
tender for orders, but an award can be made only if it is on a sound
financial footing.
It became apparent yesterday, however, that a potential bidder would have
the option of backing a bid for an order before committing itself to buying
the yard in the north east.
Mr Nick Brown, Labour MP for Newcastle upon Tyne East, said after a meeting
yesterday with defence procurement minister Mr Jonathan Aitken, that the
minister had confirmed that if a potential purchaser were willing to offer
the guarantees the MoD required it would be possible for the department to
place a contract with the yard.
Mr Brown said: 'This gives the company the chance to make the transition
from receivership to private ownership on the back of an award of a contract
from the MoD.'
Swan Hunter's remaining 1,080 employees are fitting out its last orders  -
two Type 23 frigates.
The company's sale prospects could be greatly enhanced if it could win the
refit of the Royal Fleet Auxiliary supply vessel Sir Bedivere, for which the
MoD has invited tenders by the end of March. The refit will cost about
Pounds 30m.
At the meeting with Mr Aitken Mr Brown and Mr Stephen Byers, Wallsend Labour
MP, expressed concern that rival bidders might try to delay the tendering
process, knowing that the order could be critical to Swan Hunter. Mr Aitken
said he would be sensitive to delaying tactics.
Mr Ed James of receivers Price Waterhouse welcomed the suggestion that
potential purchasers' involvement could help win MoD orders. But he added:
'The receivers still believe they will only gain work from the MoD if the
yard is financially stable, and that means finding a buyer.'
