<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / US trade gap narrows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Tumbling oil prices helped narrow the US trade gap in November by 6.7 per
cent, to Dollars 10.17bn, the Commerce Department said yesterday, Reuter
reports from Washington. In the first 11 months of last year, the trade gap
stood at an annualised Dollars 118.7bn, its highest level since Dollars
152.1bn, in 1987, the department said.
The merchandise trade deficit for October was Dollars 10.9bn, revised from a
previously reported Dollars 10.46bn. The trade deficit with Japan declined
in November to Dollars 5.72bn before seasonal adjustment, after swelling to
Dollars 6.09bn in October.
The department said imports declined by 1.5 per cent in November to Dollars
50.24bn, due largely to a sharp Dollars 115.6m drop in the cost of oil
imports to Dollars 3.09bn. Exports declined by 0.1 per cent to Dollars
40.07bn, reflecting decreases in industrial supplies and materials.
